anian-German neurosurgeon that has been the president of the [[International Society for Neurosurgery]].}}</ref> [[neurosurgeon]] and medical scientist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.payvand.com/news/14/sep/1023.html|title=Iran starts building Mideast largest oncology center in Rasht|work=payvand.com}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[Image:Hannover INI.jpg|thumb|239 px|left|[[International Neuroscience Institute]] ([[:de:International Neuroscience Institdssute|in Deutsch]]) in [[Hannover]], founded by Samii]]\nSamii was born in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] on 19 June 1937.<ref name=\"superuser\"/> He is of [[Gilak]] origin, and his family hails from [[Gilan]]. He moved back to [[Rasht, Iran]] for a short period in order to improve his [[Gilaki language|Gilaki]]. After having completed his high school education in Iran, he moved to Germany, where he started his medical studies at the [[University of Mainz]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.professormadjidsamii.com/en/biography.html|website=Professor Madjid Samii - official website|accessdate=27 January 2016}}</ref> \n\nHe has been the president of the International Society for Neurosurgery and was elected as the founding president of the [[Congress of International Neurosurgeons]] (MASCIN) in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emn-neurotrauma.de/news.htm|title=EMN e.V. - News<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|access-date=2007-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209110251/http://www.emn-neurotrauma.de/news.htm|archive-date=2012-02-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSamii received the \"Physician\" award by the north German city of [[Hanover]]. Former German chancellor [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] hailed the 70-year-old Samii for his medical contribution to neuroscience as head of the International Neuroscience Institute (INI), based in Hanover.\n\nHe is the president of the International Neuroscience Institute (INI).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ini-hannover.de/en/home.html|title=Home - INI Hannover EN|website=www.ini-hannover.de|language=en|access-date=2018-01-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he received the \"Friendship Award\", from the Prime minister of China for his contribution to the medical progress of the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theniki.net/newsdetail-en-31.html|title=China to Honor prominent Iranian Neurosurgeon<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|access-date=2007-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090328124121/http://www.theniki.net/newsdetail-en-31.html|archive-date=2009-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe had earlier received the 2014 [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize|Leibniz Ring Prize]] in Berlin.<ref name=\"presstv.ir\">{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2014/10/11/381838/iran-scientist-wins-golden-neuron-award/|title=PressTV-Iran scientist wins Golden Neuron Award|work=presstv.ir}}</ref>[[Image:Majid Samii 1.jpg|thumb|239 px|Samii speaking at the 5th Symposium of World Federation of Neurology, [[Milad Tower]], [[Tehran]]]]\n\n==Present duties<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madjidsamiisociety.org/cv.php|title=MASSIN|work=madjidsamiisociety.org|access-date=2013-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160929211509/http://www.madjidsamiisociety.org/cv.php|archive-date=2016-09-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>==\n\n* President of the International Neuroscience Institute (INI) at Otto von Guericke University President of the China INI at Capital University in Beijing\n* President of the Neurobionic Foundation\n* President of the Board of Trustees of AWD Children\u2019s Assistance Foundation\n* Director emeritus of the Neurosurgical Clinic, Nordstadt Hospital in Hannover\n* Honorary President of the World Federation of Neurosurgical Societies (WFNS)\n* Honorary President of the World Federation of Neurosurgical Societies Endowment/Foundation (WFNS)\n* Honorary President of the German Society of Skull Base Surgery\n* Honorary President of CURAC - German Society of Computer and Robot-Assisted Surgery\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2001: Honorary President of ''The World Federation of Neurosurgical Societies''<ref>[http://www.wfns.org/pages/wfns_honorary_presidents/19.php - World Federation of Neurosurgical Societies, List of Honorary Presidents] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091115061800/http://www.wfns.org/pages/wfns_honorary_presidents/19.php |date=2009-11-15 }}, retrieved 30 September 2009</ref>\n* 2005: [[Carl Zeiss]] Honorary Lecture and Visiting Professorship initiated and hosted by the Department of Neurosurgery of the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Johann Wolfgang Goethe-University]], [[Frankfurt am Main]], Germany<ref>[http://www.zeiss.com/C125722800455536/0/84ABA0A7E020A404C125735600258B86/$File/informed03_3538.pdf Volker Seifert: Description of the Carl Zeiss Honorary Lecture and Visiting Professorship, in: Department of Neurosurgery of the Johann Wolfgang Goethe-University, Frankfurt am Main, Germany, September 2007, retrieved 30 September 2009]</ref>\n* 2006: [[Iranian Science and Culture Hall of Fame]]\n* World Physician 2007\n* 2007: [[Friendship Award (China)|Friendship Award]] of the People's Republic of China.\n* 2010: Neurosurgical Society of America Medal Recipient.\n* 2013: {{ill|Leibniz-Ring-Hannover|de}} Prize winner.<ref name=\"presstv.ir\"/>\n* 2014: World top neurosurgeon and Golden Neuron Award Winner.<ref name=\"burakyildirim\">{{cite web|url=http://worldacademyns.org/default.aspx?sid=10|title=Golden Neuron Award Winners|author=Burak YILDIRIM|work=worldacademyns.org|access-date=2014-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801051228/http://worldacademyns.org/default.aspx?sid=10|archive-date=2017-08-01|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"presstv.ir\"/>\n* 2017: Awarded Honorary Doctorate title by [[Uskudar University]] for his valuable global researches and clinical contributions in Neuroscience<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uskudar.edu.tr/en/icerik/2487/uskudar-universitys-honorary-doctorate-ceremony-to-world-famous-neurosurgeon-prof-madjid-samii|title=\u00dcsk\u00fcdar University's Honorary Doctorate Ceremony to World-Famous Neurosurgeon Prof. Madjid Samii|first=\u00dcSK\u00dcDAR|last=\u00dcN\u0130VERS\u0130TES\u0130|publisher=}}</ref>.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Category:Majid Samii}}\n* [http://www.hgiocoli.com/img/cvsamii.pdf Curriculum Vitae of Majid Samii - up to 1988]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Q5UqBAAAQBAJ&pg=PR7&lpg=PR7&dq=where+is+professor+samii+born%3F&source=bl&ots=uiz9QBu5E9&sig=3cyeOftGdNr_ytHCCrO5xI4Xh0Y&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9bwTVM6BMuq1sQSL7oC4BQ&ved=0CEsQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=where%20is%20professor%20samii%20born%3F&f=false \"Samii's Essentials in Neurosurgery\"]\n*[https://www.radiozamaneh.com/304467 www.radiozamaneh.com]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Samii, Madjid}}\n[[Category:Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category:Iranian expatriate academics]]\n[[Category:Iranian surgeons]]\n[[Category:Iranian inventors]]\n[[Category:People from Tehran]]\n[[Category:German people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Germany]]\n[[Category:German neurosurgeons]]\n[[Category:German inventors]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Bettyboop2499", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Majid_Samii"}
{"title_page": "Applied Physics Laboratory", "text_new": "{{other uses2|APL}}\n{{short description|University-affiliated research center}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Laboratory\n| name             = Applied Physics Laboratory\n| motto            =\n| image            = JHU APL logo.png\n| established      = 1942\n| director         = Dr. Ralph Semmel\n| city             = [[North Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| budget           =\n| type             = Unclassified / classified\n| staff            = 6300<ref name=aboutapl>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/About |title=About APL|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n| campus           =\n| nobel_laureates  =\n| operating_agency = [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n| website          = {{url|https://www.jhuapl.edu/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory''', commonly known as simply the '''Applied Physics Laboratory''', or '''APL''', located in [[Howard County, Maryland]], near [[Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]] and [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]], is a not-for-profit, [[University Affiliated Research Center|university-affiliated research center]] (or UARC) employing 6300 people (2018). The Lab serves as a technical resource for the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], [[NASA]], and other government agencies. APL has developed numerous systems and technologies in the areas of air and missile defense, surface and undersea naval warfare, [[computer security]], and space science and spacecraft construction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/default.asp |title=Archived copy|access-date=January 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120193903/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/default.asp |archive-date=January 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> While APL provides research and engineering services to the government, it is not a traditional [[defense contractor]], as it is a UARC and a division of [[Johns Hopkins University]]. APL is a scientific and engineering research and development division, rather than an academic division, of Johns Hopkins.\n\nHopkins' [[Whiting School of Engineering]] offers part-time graduate programs through its Engineering for Professionals program. Courses are taught at seven locations in the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]], including the APL Education Center.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|title=APL Education Center|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=October 15, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420062006/http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|archive-date=April 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAPL was created in 1942 during [[World War II]] under the Office of Scientific Research and Development as part of the Government's effort to mobilize the nation's science and engineering expertise within its universities. Its founding director was [[Merle Tuve|Merle Anthony Tuve]]. The Laboratory succeeded in developing the [[Proximity fuze|variable-time proximity fuze]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.jhu.edu/~jhumag/0400web/10.html|first=Joanne|last=Simpson|title=The Funny Little Fuze with Devastating Aim|journal=Johns Hopkins Magazine|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|date=April 2000}}</ref> that played a significant role in the Allied victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|title=Our History|accessdate=March 12, 2015|website=JHU APL|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015083216/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|archive-date=October 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In response to the fuze's success, the APL created the MK 57 gun director in 1944. Pleased with the APL's work, the Navy then tasked it with the mission to find a way to negate guided missile threats. From there on, the APL became very involved in wartime research.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|title = APL at 70|date=2012|accessdate=March 12, 2015|website=JHU APL|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015083216/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|archive-date=October 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Expected to disband at the end of the war, APL instead became heavily involved in the development of guided missile technology for the Navy. At governmental request, the University continued to maintain the Laboratory as a public service.\n\nAPL was originally located in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]] in a used-car garage<ref name=\":2\"/> at the former [[Wolf Motor Company]] building at 8621 Georgia Avenue.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vFX-vGYz7FgC&pg=PA111|title=Historic Silver Spring|isbn=978-0-7385-4188-4|last1=McCoy|first1=Jerry A|last2 = Society|first2=Silver Spring Historical|date=November 2005}}</ref> APL moved to Laurel beginning in 1954, with the construction of a two million dollar building and a US$700,000 wing expansion in 1956.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Washington Post|title=Johns Hopkins Lets Contract in Md.|date=March 27, 1955}}</ref> The final staff transitioned to the new facility in 1975.<ref name=\":2\">http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/td2104/hagler.pdf {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911232526/http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/td2104/hagler.pdf|date=September 11, 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jhu.edu/~gazette/2002/25mar02/25sixty.html The Johns Hopkins Gazette: March 25, 2002<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Before moving to Laurel, APL also maintained the \"Forest Grove Station\", north of Silver Spring on Georgia Avenue near today's Forest Glen Metro,<ref>[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=forest+grove,+maryland&ie=UTF8&z=16&iwloc=addr Google Maps<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which included a hypersonic wind tunnel. The Forest Grove Station was vacated and torn down in 1963 and flight simulations were moved to Laurel.\n\nThe Laboratory's name comes from its origins in [[World War II]], but APL's major strengths are [[systems engineering]] and technology application. More than three-quarters of the staff are technical professionals, and 25% have [[computer science]] and math degrees. APL conducts programs in fundamental and applied research; exploratory and advanced development; test and evaluation; and systems engineering and integration.\n\n=== Wartime contributions ===\nDuring the 1950s and the 1960s APL worked with the US Navy in the [[Operation Bumblebee]] Program on the [[Talos missile]], [[Tartar missile]], Terrier, and [[RIM-2 Terrier]] Surface to Air Missile systems. The follow-on [[RIM-50 Typhon]] Missile Project, based on improved Talos and Tartar Missiles, while successful, was cancelled in 1963 due to high costs and was eventually developed into the now well known [[Aegis Combat System]] based on an improved Terrier.\n\nIn 1990, APL became involved with [[Operation Desert Storm]] and was involved in the {{clarify|text=Gulf Crisis Room|date=August 2015}} among other efforts. In the same decade (1992), APL, along with [[Johns Hopkins University]], developed an algorithm that allowed for automatic mammogram analysis.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n=== Pershing ===\nIn 1965, the US Army contracted with APL to develop and implement a test and evaluation program for the [[Pershing missile]] systems.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mentzer, Jr.|first=William R.|title=Test and Evaluation of Land-Mobile Missile Systems|journal=Johns Hopkins APL Technical Digest|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|date=1998|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/TD/td1904/mentzer.pdf}}</ref> APL developed the Pershing Operational Test Program (OTP), provided technical support to the [[Pershing Operational Test Unit]] (POTU), identified problem areas and improved the performance and survivability of the Pershing systems.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lyman|first=Donald R.|title=POTU: Testing Pershing in Europe and CONUS|journal=Field Artillery Journal|pages=15\u201317|date=May\u2013June 1977|url=http://sill-www.army.mil/firesbulletin/archives/1977/MAY_JUN_1977/MAY_JUN_1977_PAGES_15_17.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nThe modern Applied Physics Laboratory is located in [[Laurel, Maryland]], and spans 453 acres with more than 30 buildings on site. Additional auxiliary campuses exist in the surrounding areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/About|title=About:JHU{{!}}APL}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAPL is also home to a Johns Hopkins graduate program in engineering and applied sciences, called Engineering for Professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|title=JHU Graduate Program in Engineering and Applied Sciences|website=JHU APL|accessdate=March 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420062006/http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|archive-date=April 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Courses are taught at seven locations in the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]], including the APL Education Center.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Research==\nAs of APL's 70th anniversary in 2012, there were over 600 projects in progress, spanning from those in APL's more traditional areas of work, including air defense, undersea warfare precision engagement and strategic systems to newer types of projects, including those in homeland security and cyber operations.<ref name=\":0\"/> Due to the nature of the APL's work, many of its projects' details are kept confidential.\n\n=== Defense ===\nThe [[U.S. Navy]] continues to be APL's primary long-term sponsor. The Laboratory performs work for the [[Missile Defense Agency]], the [[Department of Homeland Security]], intelligence agencies, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency ([[DARPA]]), and others. The Laboratory supports NASA through space science, [[spacecraft]] design and fabrication, and mission operations. APL has made significant contributions in the areas of air defense, strike and power projection, [[submarine]] security, antisubmarine warfare, strategic systems evaluation, command and control, distributed information and display systems, sensors, information processing, and space systems.\n\n=== Space ===\n[[File:Alan Stern and New Horizons Team Celebrate Pluto Flyby.jpg|thumb|350px|[[Alan Stern]] celebrating the successful flyby of the [[Pluto]] system by [[New Horizons]] in 2015 in the APL Mission Operations Center.]]\nAPL has built and operated many spacecraft, including [[Transit (satellite)|the TRANSIT navigation system]], [[NEAR Shoemaker|NEAR]], [[Geosat]], [[Advanced Composition Explorer|ACE]], [[TIMED]], [[CONTOUR]], [[MESSENGER]], [[Van Allen Probes]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/newscenter/pressreleases/spacemission/spmissions.asp|title=Space Press Releases |last=|first=|date= |website=JHU APL|publisher=|accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref> the [[New Horizons]] mission to [[Pluto]], the [[Parker Solar Probe]] mission to the outer corona of the Sun,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu|title=Parker Solar Probe: A Nasa Mission to Touch the Sun|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2014|website=JHU APL|publisher=|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> and [[STEREO]].<ref name=\":1\"/> In 2019, the APL proposed [[Dragonfly (spacecraft)|Dragonfly]] mission was selected as the fourth NASA [[New Frontiers program#Fourth mission|New Frontiers mission]].<ref name='Foust 2019'>[https://spacenews.com/nasa-selects-titan-drone-for-next-new-frontiers-mission/ NASA selects Titan drone for next New Frontiers mission]. Jeff Foust, ''Space News''. June 27, 2019. Retrieved July 6, 2019.</ref><ref name='NASA 2019'>[https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-announces-new-solar-system-mission NASA's Dragonfly Will Fly Around Titan Looking for Origins, Signs of Life]. ''NASA''. June 27, 2019. Retrieved July 6, 2019.</ref> Dragonfly is a lander for Saturn's moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] that will fly using rotors in a dual-quadcopter configuration to move around the moon's surface.\n\nThe [[asteroid]] [[132524 APL]] was named in honor of APL after a flyby by the New Horizons spacecraft.\n\n=== Prosthetics ===\nIn 2014, APL made history with the successful use of the ''Modular Prosthetic Limb'' \u2014 a fully artificial articulated arm and hand \u2014 by a bilateral shoulder-level [[amputee]]. APL used pattern recognition algorithms to track which muscles were contracting and enable the prosthetics to move in conjunction with the amputee's body.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/newscenter/pressreleases/2014/141216.asp|title=Amputee Makes History with APL's Modular Prosthetic Limb|last=|first=|date=December 16, 2014|website=JHU APL |publisher= |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimilar technology was used in 2016 for a demonstration in which a paralyzed man was able to \"fist-bump\" [[Barack Obama]] using signals sent from an implanted [[brain chip]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/video/watch-obama-fist-bump-a-robotic-arm-powered-by-a-brain-chip-785470531610|title=Watch Obama fist bump a robotic arm powered by a brain chip|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-07-21|language=en}}</ref> The limb returned sensory feedback from the arm to the wearer's brain.\n\n===Drones===\nThe APL researches and produces [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s for the US military.<ref name=JHUDronesPanel>{{cite web|title=Drone Research and Robotic Warfare: The Hopkins Connection |url=http://web.jhu.edu/announcements/faculty-staff/targetpage.html?baid=38392|work=Today's Announcements|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|accessdate=August 13, 2012|date=April 20, 2012}}</ref> One of its most recent projects is an unmanned aerial swarm that can be controlled by a single operator on the ground.<ref name=AMD13Aug2012>{{cite news|title=Demonstrating Expanded Control of UAV Swarm|url=||newspaper=Aerospace Manufacturing and Design|date=August 13, 2012|author=Manufacturing Group|quote=Boeing and the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory (JHU/APL) have demonstrated that an operator on the ground, using only a laptop and a military radio, can command an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) \"swarm\". Despite limited flight training, the operator was able to connect with autonomous UAVs, task them and obtain information without using a ground control station. [...] The demonstrations are conducted under a collaborative agreement between Boeing and JHU/APL, a University Affiliated Research Center and a division of Johns Hopkins University that has been addressing critical national challenges through the innovative application of science and technology for nearly 70 years. It maintains a staff of about 5,000 on its Laurel, Maryland, campus.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States college laboratories conducting basic defense research]]\n*[[Stamatios Krimigis|Tom Krimigis]]\n*[[Michael D. Griffin]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jhuapl.edu/ APL home page]\n{{JHU}}\n{{coord|39|09|55|N|76|53|50|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University]]\n[[Category:Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Physics laboratories]]\n[[Category:University and college laboratories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1942]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Space technology research institutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|University-affiliated research center}}\n{{other uses2|APL}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Laboratory\n| name             = Applied Physics Laboratory\n| motto            =\n| image            = JHU APL logo.png\n| established      = 1942\n| director         = Dr. Ralph Semmel\n| city             = [[North Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| budget           =\n| type             = Unclassified / classified\n| staff            = 6300<ref name=aboutapl>{{cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/About |title=About APL|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n| campus           =\n| nobel_laureates  =\n| operating_agency = [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n| website          = {{url|https://www.jhuapl.edu/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory''', commonly known as simply the '''Applied Physics Laboratory''', or '''APL''', located in [[Howard County, Maryland]], near [[Laurel, Maryland|Laurel]] and [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]], is a not-for-profit, [[University Affiliated Research Center|university-affiliated research center]] (or UARC) employing 6300 people (2018). The Lab serves as a technical resource for the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], [[NASA]], and other government agencies. APL has developed numerous systems and technologies in the areas of air and missile defense, surface and undersea naval warfare, [[computer security]], and space science and spacecraft construction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/default.asp |title=Archived copy|access-date=January 17, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120193903/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/default.asp |archive-date=January 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> While APL provides research and engineering services to the government, it is not a traditional [[defense contractor]], as it is a UARC and a division of [[Johns Hopkins University]]. APL is a scientific and engineering research and development division, rather than an academic division, of Johns Hopkins.\n\nHopkins' [[Whiting School of Engineering]] offers part-time graduate programs through its Engineering for Professionals program. Courses are taught at seven locations in the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]], including the APL Education Center.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|title=APL Education Center|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory|access-date=October 15, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420062006/http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|archive-date=April 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAPL was created in 1942 during [[World War II]] under the Office of Scientific Research and Development as part of the Government's effort to mobilize the nation's science and engineering expertise within its universities. Its founding director was [[Merle Tuve|Merle Anthony Tuve]]. The Laboratory succeeded in developing the [[Proximity fuze|variable-time proximity fuze]]<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.jhu.edu/~jhumag/0400web/10.html|first=Joanne|last=Simpson|title=The Funny Little Fuze with Devastating Aim|journal=Johns Hopkins Magazine|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|date=April 2000}}</ref> that played a significant role in the Allied victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|title=Our History|accessdate=March 12, 2015|website=JHU APL|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015083216/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|archive-date=October 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In response to the fuze's success, the APL created the MK 57 gun director in 1944. Pleased with the APL's work, the Navy then tasked it with the mission to find a way to negate guided missile threats. From there on, the APL became very involved in wartime research.<ref name=\":0\"> {{Cite web|url = http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|title = APL at 70|date=2012|accessdate=March 12, 2015|website=JHU APL|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015083216/http://www.jhuapl.edu/aboutapl/heritage/default.asp|archive-date=October 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Expected to disband at the end of the war, APL instead became heavily involved in the development of guided missile technology for the Navy. At governmental request, the University continued to maintain the Laboratory as a public service.\n\nAPL was originally located in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]] in a used-car garage<ref name=\":2\"/> at the former [[Wolf Motor Company]] building at 8621 Georgia Avenue.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vFX-vGYz7FgC&pg=PA111|title=Historic Silver Spring|isbn=978-0-7385-4188-4|last1=McCoy|first1=Jerry A|last2 = Society|first2=Silver Spring Historical|date=November 2005}}</ref> APL moved to Laurel beginning in 1954, with the construction of a two million dollar building and a US$700,000 wing expansion in 1956.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Washington Post|title=Johns Hopkins Lets Contract in Md.|date=March 27, 1955}}</ref> The final staff transitioned to the new facility in 1975.<ref name=\":2\">http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/td2104/hagler.pdf {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911232526/http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/td2104/hagler.pdf|date=September 11, 2006}}</ref><ref>[http://www.jhu.edu/~gazette/2002/25mar02/25sixty.html The Johns Hopkins Gazette: March 25, 2002<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Before moving to Laurel, APL also maintained the \"Forest Grove Station\", north of Silver Spring on Georgia Avenue near today's Forest Glen Metro,<ref>[https://maps.google.com/maps?f=q&hl=en&geocode=&q=forest+grove,+maryland&ie=UTF8&z=16&iwloc=addr Google Maps<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> which included a hypersonic wind tunnel. The Forest Grove Station was vacated and torn down in 1963 and flight simulations were moved to Laurel.\n\nThe Laboratory's name comes from its origins in [[World War II]], but APL's major strengths are [[systems engineering]] and technology application. More than three-quarters of the staff are technical professionals, and 25% have [[computer science]] and math degrees. APL conducts programs in fundamental and applied research; exploratory and advanced development; test and evaluation; and systems engineering and integration.\n\n=== Wartime contributions ===\nDuring the 1950s and the 1960s APL worked with the US Navy in the [[Operation Bumblebee]] Program on the [[Talos missile]], [[Tartar missile]], Terrier, and [[RIM-2 Terrier]] Surface to Air Missile systems. The follow-on [[RIM-50 Typhon]] Missile Project, based on improved Talos and Tartar Missiles, while successful, was cancelled in 1963 due to high costs and was eventually developed into the now well known [[Aegis Combat System]] based on an improved Terrier.\n\nIn 1990, APL became involved with [[Operation Desert Storm]] and was involved in the {{clarify|text=Gulf Crisis Room|date=August 2015}} among other efforts. In the same decade (1992), APL, along with [[Johns Hopkins University]], developed an algorithm that allowed for automatic mammogram analysis.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n=== Pershing ===\nIn 1965, the US Army contracted with APL to develop and implement a test and evaluation program for the [[Pershing missile]] systems.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mentzer, Jr.|first=William R.|title=Test and Evaluation of Land-Mobile Missile Systems|journal=Johns Hopkins APL Technical Digest|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|date=1998|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/TD/td1904/mentzer.pdf}}</ref> APL developed the Pershing Operational Test Program (OTP), provided technical support to the [[Pershing Operational Test Unit]] (POTU), identified problem areas and improved the performance and survivability of the Pershing systems.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lyman|first=Donald R.|title=POTU: Testing Pershing in Europe and CONUS|journal=Field Artillery Journal|pages=15\u201317|date=May\u2013June 1977|url=http://sill-www.army.mil/firesbulletin/archives/1977/MAY_JUN_1977/MAY_JUN_1977_PAGES_15_17.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nThe modern Applied Physics Laboratory is located in [[Laurel, Maryland]], and spans 453 acres with more than 30 buildings on site. Additional auxiliary campuses exist in the surrounding areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/About|title=About:JHU{{!}}APL}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nAPL is also home to a Johns Hopkins graduate program in engineering and applied sciences, called Engineering for Professionals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|title=JHU Graduate Program in Engineering and Applied Sciences|website=JHU APL|accessdate=March 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420062006/http://www.jhuapl.edu/education/edcenter/|archive-date=April 20, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Courses are taught at seven locations in the [[Baltimore-Washington Metropolitan Area]], including the APL Education Center.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Research==\nAs of APL's 70th anniversary in 2012, there were over 600 projects in progress, spanning from those in APL's more traditional areas of work, including air defense, undersea warfare precision engagement and strategic systems to newer types of projects, including those in homeland security and cyber operations.<ref name=\":0\"/> Due to the nature of the APL's work, many of its projects' details are kept confidential.\n\n=== Defense ===\nThe [[U.S. Navy]] continues to be APL's primary long-term sponsor. The Laboratory performs work for the [[Missile Defense Agency]], the [[Department of Homeland Security]], intelligence agencies, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency ([[DARPA]]), and others. The Laboratory supports NASA through space science, [[spacecraft]] design and fabrication, and mission operations. APL has made significant contributions in the areas of air defense, strike and power projection, [[submarine]] security, antisubmarine warfare, strategic systems evaluation, command and control, distributed information and display systems, sensors, information processing, and space systems.\n\n=== Space ===\n[[File:Alan Stern and New Horizons Team Celebrate Pluto Flyby.jpg|thumb|350px|[[Alan Stern]] celebrating the successful flyby of the [[Pluto]] system by [[New Horizons]] in 2015 in the APL Mission Operations Center.]]\nAPL has built and operated many spacecraft, including [[Transit (satellite)|the TRANSIT navigation system]], [[NEAR Shoemaker|NEAR]], [[Geosat]], [[Advanced Composition Explorer|ACE]], [[TIMED]], [[CONTOUR]], [[MESSENGER]], [[Van Allen Probes]],<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/newscenter/pressreleases/spacemission/spmissions.asp|title=Space Press Releases |last=|first=|date= |website=JHU APL|publisher=|accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref> the [[New Horizons]] mission to [[Pluto]], the [[Parker Solar Probe]] mission to the outer corona of the Sun,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu|title=Parker Solar Probe: A Nasa Mission to Touch the Sun|last=|first=|date=March 18, 2014|website=JHU APL|publisher=|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> and [[STEREO]].<ref name=\":1\"/> In 2019, the APL proposed [[Dragonfly (spacecraft)|Dragonfly]] mission was selected as the fourth NASA [[New Frontiers program#Fourth mission|New Frontiers mission]].<ref name='Foust 2019'>[https://spacenews.com/nasa-selects-titan-drone-for-next-new-frontiers-mission/ NASA selects Titan drone for next New Frontiers mission]. Jeff Foust, ''Space News''. June 27, 2019. Retrieved July 6, 2019.</ref><ref name='NASA 2019'>[https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-announces-new-solar-system-mission NASA's Dragonfly Will Fly Around Titan Looking for Origins, Signs of Life]. ''NASA''. June 27, 2019. Retrieved July 6, 2019.</ref> Dragonfly is a lander for Saturn's moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]] that will fly using rotors in a dual-quadcopter configuration to move around the moon's surface.\n\nThe [[asteroid]] [[132524 APL]] was named in honor of APL after a flyby by the New Horizons spacecraft.\n\n=== Prosthetics ===\nIn 2014, APL made history with the successful use of the ''Modular Prosthetic Limb'' \u2014 a fully artificial articulated arm and hand \u2014 by a bilateral shoulder-level [[amputee]]. APL used pattern recognition algorithms to track which muscles were contracting and enable the prosthetics to move in conjunction with the amputee's body.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jhuapl.edu/newscenter/pressreleases/2014/141216.asp|title=Amputee Makes History with APL's Modular Prosthetic Limb|last=|first=|date=December 16, 2014|website=JHU APL |publisher= |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimilar technology was used in 2016 for a demonstration in which a paralyzed man was able to \"fist-bump\" [[Barack Obama]] using signals sent from an implanted [[brain chip]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/video/watch-obama-fist-bump-a-robotic-arm-powered-by-a-brain-chip-785470531610|title=Watch Obama fist bump a robotic arm powered by a brain chip|work=NBC News|access-date=2018-07-21|language=en}}</ref> The limb returned sensory feedback from the arm to the wearer's brain.\n\n===Drones===\nThe APL researches and produces [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s for the US military.<ref name=JHUDronesPanel>{{cite web|title=Drone Research and Robotic Warfare: The Hopkins Connection |url=http://web.jhu.edu/announcements/faculty-staff/targetpage.html?baid=38392|work=Today's Announcements|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|accessdate=August 13, 2012|date=April 20, 2012}}</ref> One of its most recent projects is an unmanned aerial swarm that can be controlled by a single operator on the ground.<ref name=AMD13Aug2012>{{cite news|title=Demonstrating Expanded Control of UAV Swarm|url=||newspaper=Aerospace Manufacturing and Design|date=August 13, 2012|author=Manufacturing Group|quote=Boeing and the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory (JHU/APL) have demonstrated that an operator on the ground, using only a laptop and a military radio, can command an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) \"swarm\". Despite limited flight training, the operator was able to connect with autonomous UAVs, task them and obtain information without using a ground control station. [...] The demonstrations are conducted under a collaborative agreement between Boeing and JHU/APL, a University Affiliated Research Center and a division of Johns Hopkins University that has been addressing critical national challenges through the innovative application of science and technology for nearly 70 years. It maintains a staff of about 5,000 on its Laurel, Maryland, campus.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States college laboratories conducting basic defense research]]\n*[[Stamatios Krimigis|Tom Krimigis]]\n*[[Michael D. Griffin]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jhuapl.edu/ APL home page]\n{{JHU}}\n{{coord|39|09|55|N|76|53|50|W|region:US-MD_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University]]\n[[Category:Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Physics laboratories]]\n[[Category:University and college laboratories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1942]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Laurel, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Space technology research institutes]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applied_Physics_Laboratory"}
